<DOC><DOCNO> AP880226-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0151EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Fighting     02-26 0311</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador-Fighting,0324</SECOND><HEAD>Salvador Rebels Lift Transport Ban</HEAD><BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas called anend to their transportation ban Thursday. At least three civilianswere killed and eight wounded during the three days it lasted,police said.   The guerrillas announced Monday on their clandestine RadioVenceremos that all vehicles defying the ban risked attack.   Police said guerrillas damaged four vehicles and a gasolinestation during the ban.   The five leftist guerrilla groups which form the Farabundo MartiNational Liberation Front denied responsibility for civiliancasualties in a statement broadcast over Radio Venceremos.   They blamed the U.S.-supported government of President JoseNapoleon Duarte, saying the dead and injured were part of ``anorchestrated campaign ... with the brutal intention ofincriminating'' the guerrillas for civilian casualties.   The broadcast claimed the guerrillas sabotaged 30 electricaldistribution structures and killed or wounded 45 soldiers duringthe transport ban.   A land mine exploded Thursday as an army patrol sought todismantle a barricade on the Pan American Highway, wounding fivefarmers and one soldier, according to judicial sources in Ilobasco,about 35 miles northeast of the capital.   City and rural traffic returned to normal Thursday. Dozens oftrucks, waiting at the Guatemalan and Honduran borders until theban ended, entered El Salvador, customs and migration officialssaid.   Police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, saidearlier this week that three workers were killed and five woundedwhen guerrillas attacked a bus on a highway 10 miles northeast ofSan Salvador.   Police reported that in another incident, on the south side ofthe capital, three civilians were injured when suspected guerrillasordered passengers off a minibus defying the ban and then tossed agrenade into it.   The rebels have called transportation bans regularly as part oftheir economic sabotage campaign during the 8-year-old civil war.</TEXT></DOC>